			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Weapon Affininty<a name="26312"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Mar 9 04 5:27 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">As I understand it (from reading previous discussions), procs work on a &quot;time since last proc&quot; system</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
wrong.
<br />

<br />
proc is based on a percentchance.
<br />

<br />
that means, if you have a weapon that swings four times per minute, your proc-chance will be like 50 % each swing at 305 dex, averaging in 2 procs per minute. if you swing 40 times, it will be 5 %, the same average 2 procs per minute.
<br />

<br />
the more swings (delay and haste come into play), the lower your proc-chance.
<br />

<br />
this has basically been proven by some warriors, which use earthshaker (procs a PB-AOE) with AE-rampage disc (hits all mobs that are nearby). when they slowed themself (turgur from a shammy), and unequipped all haste-items, procrate went up to 70 % per hit i believe (hit per mob and number may be off). 
<br />

<br />
there are some other factors that play a role in that proc per minute (ppm) number :
<br />
1) dex (increases, formula unknown)
<br />
2) WA (increases pp, roughly 10% per point, so 3 procs per minute at 305 dex with WA5)
<br />
3) proc-rate of the weapon (datafield found, will be pointed out by lucy shortly)
<br />
4) off-hand (reduces procrate by approx 50 %, so 1,5 ppm at 305 dex with WA5)
<br />
5) not sure on that, but i think there is a melee-focus effect, that increases proc-chance (i think combat-effects, no clue though)</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="SmallText"><hr size="1" align="left" width="15%">Thorian Runesinger<br>
Veeshans Fury<br>
Bristlebane</span></td>
